<F P=106> [Report by KAZTAG correspondent for TASS] </F>
  [Text] Tokyo 7 April, TASS -- Kazakhstan supported the 
Japanese wish to become a permanent member of the UN Security 
Council and the two countries pledged to promote their political 
dialogue on international and regional issues, according to a 
joint statement signed on Thursday by Kazakh President Nursultan 
Nazarbayev and Japanese Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa. 
  Japan agreed to grant a 220-million dollar credit to 
Kazakhstan which pledged to continue market reforms, attract 
foreign investments and improve economic legislation. 
  Japan also welcomed that Kazakstan, one of the four former 
Soviet nuclear republics, had joined the nuclear 
Non-Proliferation Treaty as a nuclear-free state. The parties 
agreed to cooperate in accelerating the solution of issues 
connected with the elimination of nuclear weapons in Kazakhstan. 

